@flexiarg structure/unresolved-tensions-at-closure
@title What Tensions Would We Leave Unresolved If We Closed Here?
@sigils [🕳️/隙]
@keywords sorry, closure, void, residual, premature, tension-preservation
@audience operators at closure-adjacent hinges (ARGUE-exit, DOCUMENT-entry, or any hinge where the mission is being considered for completion)
@tone void-preserving
@factor Equanimity (upekkhā)
@references [structure/cook-ting structure/hinge-point structure/what-problem-is-this-actually-solving futon-theory/sorry-preservation]

! conclusion:
  A hinge-pool question. Plucked when a mission is approaching
  closure. The question guards against premature closure — the
  failure mode where the mission is closed because its state machine
  is at its final node, not because the tensions it arose to hold
  have finished doing their work. Sorry-preservation applied to
  process: some tensions are supposed to stay unresolved, and the
  mission's job is to preserve them, not to force them.

  + context: The mission lifecycle makes closure feel mandatory. A
    mission at DOCUMENT is supposed to DOCUMENT and finish. This is
    fine when the tensions that motivated the mission have actually
    been addressed. It is a category error when the tensions are
    still live and the mission is being closed because closing is
    the next state, not because the work is done. Closing a mission
    whose tensions are live is the same move as canonicalising a
    sorry into a proof before the sorry has been encountered as
    a sorry — it destroys the very object the mission was for.

  + WHEN-TO-PLUCK:
    - At any hinge within two hinges of planned closure
    - When the mission has produced its primary artifact and the
      temptation is to declare victory
    - When the operator notices relief at the prospect of closing,
      which is sometimes appropriate and sometimes a drift signal
    - When a reviewer or stakeholder is pressing for closure on a
      schedule external to the mission's actual progress

  + HOW-TO-ANSWER:
    1. First person. What is still pulling against what that, if
       resolved, would force a claim I cannot support from inside
       this mission?
    2. Distinguish three kinds of unresolved tension:
       a. SOLVABLE-BUT-NOT-YET: the mission could resolve this if
          it continued, and closing now would lose that chance. Do
          not close; extend.
       b. NOT-SOLVABLE-HERE: the tension is real but belongs to a
          different mission or scope. Name it, export it as a sorry,
          close this mission cleanly.
       c. STRUCTURALLY-VOID: the tension is the sorry the mission
          is supposed to preserve — collapsing it would destroy the
          mission's qualitative object. Name it, do not force
          resolution, close the mission with the void preserved in
          the journal register.
    3. Each kind wants a different action at the hinge. Misclassifying
       (a) as (b) loses work; misclassifying (b) as (c) preserves
       voids that should have been solved; misclassifying (c) as (a)
       or (b) kills the Halliday object.

  + WHAT-IT-GUARDS-AGAINST:
    - Schedule-driven closure ("we've been at this long enough")
    - Artifact-equals-mission conflation ("the WP is written, therefore
      the mission is done")
    - Loss of sorry-preservation: collapsing the typed gap into a
      prematurely-closed statement
    - "Success at the wrong exit" — mission passed its state machine's
      final node while producing no qualitative object

  + RELATIONSHIP-TO-HALLIDAY-LAYER:
    The Halliday-layer product of a mission is the class of qualitative
    objects the mission makes possible. A mission that closed with all
    tensions forced into resolution has produced a computational
    artifact (the state machine reached DOCUMENT) but no qualitative
    object (the void has been filled). A mission that closes with
    appropriate tensions preserved in the journal register has
    produced both. This question is the main diagnostic.

  + ANTI-PATTERNS-IN-ANSWERS:
    - "No unresolved tensions" — almost always a sign the question
      has not been inhabited; go back to structure/whose-question-is-this
    - Listing every minor loose end equally — (a), (b), and (c) are
      structurally different and need different handling
    - Treating (c) as a failure of the mission rather than as its gift
    - Exporting everything as a sorry into a future mission that will
      never be run — the sorry is structural, not a TODO

  + BECAUSE:
    The mission that closes correctly is the mission that stops when
    its work is done, where "work" includes tension-preservation as
    a legitimate terminal state. Cook Ting's blade does not force a
    final cut that the structure does not offer. A mission that has
    reached a joint where the tensions are (a) still resolvable in
    scope, (b) properly exported, or (c) structurally preserved —
    and acts according to which of these it is — carves the bull
    correctly.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    next[If (a): extend the mission, do not close]
    next[If (b): export the tensions as new-mission seeds, close cleanly]
    next[If (c): write the journal register's closure entry to name
         the preserved tension, close the ledger cleanly, preserve
         the void in the mission's permanent record]
